SIMPLE: segmental
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Segmental
<hw>Seg*men"tal</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Relating to, or being, a segment.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Anat. & Zool.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>Of or
pertaining to the segments of animals; <as>as, a <ex>segmental</ex>
duct; <ex>segmental</ex> papillae.</as></def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>Of or
pertaining to the segmental organs.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Segmental duct</b></col> <fld>(Anat.)</fld>, <cd>the
primitive duct of the embryonic excretory organs which gives rise to the
Wolffian duct and ureter; the pronephric duct.</cd> -- <col><b>Segmental
organs</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <fld>(Anat.)</fld> <cd>The embryonic
excretory organs of vertebrates, consisting primarily of the segmental
tubes and segmental ducts</cd>. <sd>(b)</sd> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <cd>The
tubular excretory organs, a pair of which often occur in each of several
segments in annelids. They serve as renal organs, and often, also, as
oviducts and sperm ducts.</cd> -- <col><b>Segmental tubes</b></col>
<fld>(Anat.)</fld>, <cd>the tubes which primarily open into the
segmental duct, some of which become the urinary tubules of the
adult.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Segmentation</ent>⟦br⟧
